item-identification.title: Wildlife Computers Deployment Archive Data Files
item-identification.parent-title: Satellite Telemetry Dataset: adult bearded seals in Kotzebue, Alaska (raw archive)
item-identification.abstract: The Wildlife Computers Data Portal allows users to organize deployments for each unique combination of tag and animal. Each deployment archive consists of a series of data files that can be downloaded as a single zipped archive. Most files within are comma-separated files with a few other file types. This metadata record describes entities and attributes for each of the file types that are likely to be found within an archive.
item-identification.purpose: This metadata record serves as a generic representation of deployment archives downloaded from the Wildlife Computers Data Portal
item-identification.supplemental-information: Wildlife Computers is located in Redmond, Washington, USA. https://wildlifecomputers.com/. In addition to contacting the data owners and other points of contact, Wildlife Computers may also be able to provide additional information and documentation upon request.

data-set-information.entity-attribute-overview: The entity-attributes documented here are meant to representative of the typical files found within a deployment archive pulled from the Wildlife Computers Data Portal. Exactly which files are present in an archive will vary depending upon the programming scheme and the tag hardware configuration
data-set-information.instrument: Animal Mounted Instrument - Argos Satellite Transmitter

entity-information.description: Each archive contains a series of CSV and other files. One of these is the *-Locations.csv file describing all of the location data from each deployment. At a minimum, includes Argos location estimates but may also include GPS-Fastloc location estimates (if GPS-fastloc location data are included, there will likely be two *-Locations.csv files in the archive. The second will include 'FastGPS' in the file name and this one will include both Argos and FastGPS locations). Key information for each row is date-time (UTC), latitude, longitude, quality estimate, and ellipse error information associated with each location estimate.

data-attribute.name: IQ
data-attribute.description:
This indicator gives information on the transmitter in terms of two digits, X and Y. X is the first digit and indicates residual error on the frequency calculation; Y is the second digit and indicates transmitter oscillator frequency drift between two satellite passes. Values provided in Argos DIAG format files (definition from Argos User's Manual 2011). Values obtained through some Argos channels do not include leading 0s, so 1-digit values indicate X = 0 and blank values or values of "0" indicate both X and Y = 0. Allowed values are
X=0: No calculation of residual frequency error (fewer than four messages received) X=1,2,3: Unsatisfactory convergence of calculation X=4: Residual frequency error > 1.5 Hz X=5: 0.15 Hz < residual frequency error < 1.5 Hz X=6: Residual frequency error < 0.15 Hz Y=0: No check on transmit frequency drift, as the two results are more than 12 hours apart. Y=1: Frequency discrepancy > 400 Hz Probably due to transmit frequency discrepancy, change of oscillator, etc. Y=2: Previous location is less than 1/2 hour old. Frequency discrepancy > 30 Hz, i.e. F/F (over 10 min) >2.5 E-8 Y=3: Frequency drift > 4 Hz/minute, i.e. F/F (10 min) > 1.10-7 Y=4: Frequency drift < 4 Hz/minute, i.e. F/F (10 min) < 1.10-7 Y=5: Frequency drift < 2 Hz/minute, i.e. F/F (10 min) < 5.10-8 Y=6: Frequency drift < 1 Hz/minute, i.e. F/F (10 min) < 2.5 . 10-8 Y=7: Frequency drift < 0.4 Hz/minute, i.e. F/F (10 min) < 1.10-8 Y=8: Frequency drift < 0.2 Hz/minute, i.e. F/F (10 min) < 5.10-9

entity-information.description: comma-separated file of data associated with the FastLoc GPS calculation

Depending on how the tag is programmed and the sensors onboard, a variety of behavior data can be represented in the Histos.csv file. Each record represents a type of behavior data for a given period and, then, up to 72 bin columns. What data are represented in the bin columns depends on the histogram data type and the way the tag was programmed.

data-quality.quality-control-procedures: Limited quality control procedures have been employed. This dataset is an archive of the processed output from the Wildlife Computers data processing software. These tags were deployed on free-ranging, wild animals in challenging environments. In all cases, additional quality control procedures and evaluation from experts familiar with the tags, programming and species will be required.

data-management.data-protection-plan: IT Security and Contingency Plan for the system establishes procedures and applies to the functions, operations, and resources necessary to recover and restore data as hosted in the Western Regional Support Center in Seattle, Washington, following a disruption.

lineage.lineage-statement: These data are represented as an archive of all data files pulled from the Wildlife Computers data portal. See the included R/Rmarkdown file for the R code used to download and create the archives.
